Abstract
This paper makes an important contribuon to comparave research by examining data journalism in Spain and Austria.
This paper examines the pracce of data journalism from a triple perspecve: (a) the common features of day-to-day
work, (b) the organizaonal structure and the role of the teams in newsrooms, and (c) the obstacles to and the future
of data-driven reporng. Results from content analysis of data-driven news stories in El país and Der standard (N = 136)
show dierences and similaries in the covered topics, sources, narrave style, visualizaons, interacve funcons, and
levels of transparency. Interesngly, only 36.8% of the analyzed news stories correspond to the normave expectaons
of transparency by incorporang both sources and methodological details. While the Spanish newspaper shows signi-
cantly higher levels of transparency compared with the Austrian newspaper, both newspapers perform very similarly
when it comes to providing access to raw data, which was the case in only every h news story analyzed. Findings from
focused interviews with the heads of data journalism teams deliver interesng insights into specic challenges that each
news outlet is facing when creang day-to-day data-driven news stories. This research conrms the relevance that data
journalism has achieved in countries such as Spain and demonstrates the eort of journalists in countries without access
to informaon and transparency laws to create data-driven stories.
Keywords
Data journalism; Digital journalism; Sources; Data visualizaon; Transparency; Interacvity; Journalists; Journalisc pro-

1. Introducon
Journalism has always relied on data to inform, report, combine sources, or contextualize. However, the connecon of
digitalizaon and datacaon paved the way for a new era for informaon professionals (Mayer-Schönberger; Cukier,
2013). Those changes led to “journalism’s quantave turn” (Coddington, 2015), and it reinforced professional proles
such as the data journalist with an “increased focus on measurement, outcomes assessment” (Anderson, 2015, p. 363).
The rst reference to the term “data journalism” was made more than 15 years ago, when Holovaty (2006) menoned
the need to work with spreadsheets to collate the informaon they gathered. This specializaon illustrated how the
media environment was changing and how data represented and inuenced society (Van-Dijck, 2014; Porlezza, 2019).
Arrese (2022) insists that the essence of data journalism comes from economic journalism, especially because of its
purpose: to reduce uncertainty and guide decision-making. Despite idenfying successive iniaves, the term began to
become popular, especially from 2010 onward with Wikileaks and Tim Berners-Lee’s statements, in which he assured
that the future of journalism lay in data analysis (Howard, 2014; Uskali; Kuu, 2015). The same year, The economist
published a special issue called Data, data everywhere, in which it compared data with oil, as one of the most valuable
resources (Toonders, 2014). At rst glance, there are no signicant dierences between data journalism and other pre-
vious disciplines such as precision journalism and computer-assisted journalism. However, the main disncon lies in the
big data context faced by the journalist and the needs arising from it (Gray; Bounegru; Chambers, 2012; Sandoval-Mar-
n; La-Rosa, 2018; De-Lima-Santos; Mesquita, 2021).
Data-driven journalism pracce and the corresponding academic literature have grown signicantly since 2013 (Ausser-
hofer et al., 2017; Zamith, 2019; Heravi; Lorenz, 2020). The vast majority of papers are limited to specic geographical
areas, thus oering a segmented view. Although there has been a major increase in academic aenon on underrepre-
sented regions (e.g., Mustvairo; Bebawi; Borges-Rey, 2020; Pereira; Mastrella, 2022; Camaj; Marn; Lanosga, 2022;
Kashyap; Mishra; Bhaskaran, 2022), research has mainly focused on countries with a long tradion in data journalism
(Appelgren; Lindén; Van-Dalen, 2020; De-Lima-Santos; Schapals; Bruns, 2020) such as the United Kingdom (e.g., Kni-
ght, 2015; Borges-Rey, 2016; Arias-Robles; López-López, 2020; Tong, 2021) and the United States (e.g., Parasie; Darigal,
2012; Fink; Anderson, 2015; Zamith, 2019). For this reason, Fink and Anderson (2015), Splendore et al. (2016), Cherui-
yot, Baack and Ferrer-Conill (2019), and Wright, Zamith, and Bebawi (2019) advocate for cross-naonal comparave
studies to provide in-depth understanding of the development of this specializaon and to explore the nuances of the
phenomenon.
A comparison between Spain and Austria seems parcularly suitable for this purpose: both are democrac sociees with
well-developed media systems. Lile specic research on Spanish data journalism has been published, and moreover
especially focused on specic topics such as polics, without delving into the features of day-to-day data stories and
professional rounes (Rojas-Torrijos; Rivera-Hernández, 2016; Teruel-Rodríguez; Blanco-Caslla, 2016; Córdoba-Ca-
bús, 2018; Córdoba-Cabús; García-Borrego; López-Marn, 2020; Rubio-Jordán, 2021; Arias-Robles; Carvajal, 2022).
Likewise, there are no studies related to Austrian data journalism, so this paper aims to address this research need and
provide ndings to migate this gap.
According to the categorizaon established by Hallin and Mancini (2004), Spain belongs to the polarized pluralist model
and Austria to the democrac corporast model. Nevertheless, data show how these countries converge in terms of a
high concentraon of media owners, the decline of newspaper circulaon, and the restricons on access to data due
to limitaons from legislaon (Figl, 2017; Salaverría; Gómez-Baveiredo, 2017; Grünangerl; Trappel; Tomaz, 2021). Al-
barrán (2009) and Ohlsson (2015) already introduced the idea of the hybridizaon of models and the European trend
toward homogenizaon.
The core objecve of this study is to explore data journalism pracce in Austria and Spain. More specically, this study
aims to (1) assess the content of data journalism in Spain and Austria by analyzing data-driven news stories in the Spa-
nish newspaper El país and the Austrian newspaper Der standard and (2) explore work rounes as well as the obstacles
to and future scenarios of data-driven reporng by interviewing the heads of data journalism of these news outlets.
1.1. Data journalism and access to informaon
Data journalism is a relavely young eld, so achieving an exhausve denion is rather challenging. In the literature, se-
veral aempts to dene data journalism can be idened. Howard (2014, p. 4), for instance, considered data journalism
to be a process associated with data science that encompasses “gathering, cleaning, organizing, analysing, visualizing,
and publishing data to support the creaon of acts of journalism.” Meanwhile, Veglis and Bratsas (2017, p. 111) speci-
ed that data journalists engage in the process of
“wring arcles based on the informaon and embedding visualizaons… in the arcles that help readers to
understand the signicant of the story or allow them to pinpoint data that relate to them.”
Heravi (2018, p. 3) stated that data journalism consists of
“nding stories in data –stories that are of interest to the public– and presenng these stories in the most appro-
priate manner for public use and reuse.”

Following Coddington’s denion, herein, we unders-
tand data journalism to be the result of a convergence
between dierent knowledge areas and pracces, i.e.,
as a
“hybrid form [of journalism] that encompasses stascal analysis, computer science, visualizaon and web de-
sign, and reporng” (Coddington, 2015, p. 335).
Three common components can be discerned in all of these: the exploraon of databases, the proccessing of data, and
the communicaon of results.
Focusing on the features of data journalism projects, empirical studies have shown that data-driven news stories stron-
gly rely on government and instuonal sources (Karlsson, 2010; Parasie; Darigal, 2012; Knight, 2015; De-Maeyer et al.,
2015; Cushion; Lewis; Callaghan, 2017; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Tandoc; Oh, 2017; Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Stalph,
2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Hyder; Nahid, 2019; Zamith, 2019; Zhang; Feng, 2019; Córdo-
ba-Cabús, 2020; Rubio-Jordán, 2021). The main purpose of data-driven stories is to inform and present data through
narraon and visualizaon (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Córdo-
ba-Cabús, 2020; Rubio-Jordán, 2021). The author-driven style is the most common narrave structure applied (Loosen;
Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018). Regarding transparency, prior research has found that data stories only
rarely show transparency elements such as access to the raw data (Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018;
Stalph, 2018; Zhang; Feng, 2019; Zamith, 2019; Porlezza; Splendore, 2019; Córdoba-Cabús; García-Borrego, 2021; Cha-
parro-Domínguez; Díaz-Campo, 2021). Although the ndings in terms of visualizaon in data-driven projects are mixed,
stac gures and limited use of interacve funcons seem common (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Tandoc; Oh, 2017;
Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Stalph, 2018; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Córdoba-Cabús;
García-Borrego, 2020).
The development of data journalism depends heavily on the context in which it emerges. The establishment of transpa-
rency and access-to-informaon laws encourages the emergence of data-driven projects (Parasie; Darigal, 2012; Appel-
gren; Nygren, 2014; Uskali; Kuu, 2015; De-Maeyer et al., 2015; Tabary; Provost; Troer, 2016; Appelgren; Salaverría,
2018; Sandoval-Marn; La-Rosa, 2018; Porlezza; Splendore, 2019; Tong; Zuo, 2021; Camaj; Marn; Lanosga, 2022;
Kashyap; Mishra; Bhaskaran, 2022; Tong, 2022). Hence, the most well-developed and successful data journalism is
found in countries with laws that ensure compliance with these principles (Howard, 2014; Cortés-del-Álamo; Luengo;
Elías, 2018).
In the European Union, regulaons regarding access to public documents were adopted in 2001, but the implementaon
of these regulaons diers by country (Appelgren; Salaverría, 2018). Thereaer, the European Commission adopted
the public sector informaon direcve in 2003 (Direcve 2003/98/EC), which encouraged the reuse of public data and
enabled access in digital format.
In Spain, the law on transparency, access to public informaon, and good governance was approved in 2013, and work is
currently underway to dra the corresponding regulaon together with civil society. However, this law is not in line with
European Court of Human Right’s jurisprudence, and it lacks control mechanisms to ensure compliance (Sánchez-Calero;
Mancinas-Chávez, 2017; Appelgren; Salaverría, 2018). In Austria, the constuon guarantees freedom of informaon,
but there is no specic law regulang transparency. The European Convenon on Human Rights guarantees access to
informaon, but the Austrian constuon limits this right by requiring that instuons apply discreon (Figl, 2017;
Grünangerl; Trappel; Tomaz, 2021). This may explain why Austria was at the boom of the global right to informaon
ranking in 2022, with 33 points out of 150 (RTI, 2022). In this regard, it is considered to be one of the weakest countries
in the world. Meanwhile, Spain scored 73 out of 150 points.
In Austria, data journalists “are sll a rare species” (Figl, 2017, p. 5). Unl a few years ago, data journalism was only
pracced in small newsrooms such as Dossier, the public broadcaster ORF, and the naonal newspaper Der standard.
Ocially, in 2021, the Austrian Press Agency (APA) set up the “Data + Graphics” team, which brings together experts in
data, infographics, design, and web developers. This is expected to provide visibility and value to the discipline. The rst
examples of data journalism in Spain emerged within organizaons such as Fundación Civio or Medialab-Prado in 2011.
El condencial was the rst media outlet to set up a data journalism team in 2013. However, the main generalist newspa-
per in Spain (El país) did not publish data journalism stories unl 2017, while the public broadcaster (RTVE) set up their
data team in 2019. Research focused on Spain shows a progressive upward trend in data journalism. However, except
for digital-nave media such as El condencial, Spanish newspapers did not commit to data journalism beyond specic
projects unl 2015. The health pandemic associated with the coronavirus highlighted the relevance of data journalism,
as well as the rise of stories based on gures in Spain (Córdoba-Cabús; García-Borrego; López-Marn, 2020; Costa-Sán-
chez; López-García, 2020; Sanahuja; López, 2021).

2. Methods
To answer these research quesons, we combined quantave and qualitave methods. First, we conducted a quan-
tave content analysis of data-driven news stories published in El país (Spain) and Der standard (Austria) to provide an
overview of how data are used in news stories from these news outlets (N =136). Second, we employed interviews with
two members of the data journalism teams of El país (Spain) and Der standard (Austria) to beer understand the process
of how journalists select and create news stories using data-driven techniques.
2.1. Content analysis
The quantave content analysis focused on exploring the full content of data-driven news stories published online from
1 January to 30 June 2021, in the newspapers El país (Spain) and Der standard (Austria) (N = 136). Content analysis as a
methodological tool enables one to understand the structure of stories as well as their basic components and operaon
(Igartua, 2006). These two newspapers were selected because they are the naonal newspapers most trusted by the
populaon –48% and 69%, respecvely– according to the Digital news report (Reuters Instute, 2021). They both have a
data team in their newsroom and the highest online reach (21% and 20%, respecvely) in the last year (Reuters Instute,
2021). We created a codebook consisng of formal categories (medium, date of publicaon, headline, secon, and link)
and categories that aimed to capture the content of data-driven news stories. Specically, the proposed categories can
be grouped into three dimensions: story features, data, and visualizaons (Table 1).

The variables examined in the rst dimension are specied below.
Topics
Based on dierent categorizaons proposed by Loosen, Reimer, and Schmidt (2017), Tandoc and Oh (2017), and Stalph
(2018), the following list of topics was created: (1) polics; (2) society; (3) economics and business; (4) health, science,
and environment; (5) educaon; (6) sports; (7) culture and art; and (8) entertainment.
Sources
Building on prior research (Knight, 2015; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017), we encoded the types of sources used in the
analyzed news stories. We coded the number of included personal sources, the types of sources, and the aribuon.
Narrave style
It was coded as follows: (a) explanatory or author-driven style, that is, a heavy message load and reduced interacvity;
(b) exploratory or reader-driven style, that is, no specic order and free interacon; and (c) hybrid, that is, a combinaon
(Segel; Heer, 2010).
Type of story
Building on the conceptualizaon of Rogers (2014) and based on the type of data and the methods employed, we disn-
guished between the following types of data journalism projects: (1) by just the facts (includes public data and produces
a visualizaon), (2) data-driven news stories (refers to issues that are in the public eye and reveals the numbers behind
the news), (3) analysis and background (explains the facts behind the news by providing a thorough analysis and detailed
informaon), and (4) deep invesgaons (in-depth research on large datasets).
Temporal dimension, focus, purpose, way of communicang
Both the me and focus dimensions were delimited according to criteria from Davenport (2014). In line with Gray, Bou-
negru, and Chambers (2012), we selected the purpose of the story, while the way in which data were communicated
was determined by using the classicaon from Bradshaw (2011): visualize, narrate, socialize, humanize, personalize,
and ulize.
Data
Focusing on the data dimension, we also analyzed the number, the type, and the aribuon of data sources (Knight,
2015; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017). Moreover, the level of transparency in terms of access to raw data and incorpo-
raon of methodological details was also assessed (Hayes; Singer; Ceppos, 2007; Karlsson, 2010; Parasie; Darigal, 2012;
Tandoc; Oh, 2017; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Stalph, 2018; Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Zamith, 2019; Zang; Feng, 2019).
Visualizaons
Finally, building on Córdoba-Cabús and García-Borrego (2020), we coded the type of visualizaon as the third dimension of
Table 1: (1) tables and lists, (2) stac graphs, (3) interacve graphs, (4) maps with or without interacvity, (5) visual resour-
ces, (6) animaons, and (7) infographics. In so doing, we also examined the acons that the audience can conduct with the
visualizaons, i.e., the interacvity (Schulmeister, 2003; Yi; Ah-Kang; Stasko, 2007; Boy, Deene; Fekete, 2015).

2.2. Data analysis
Data were analyzed using SPSS (version 25.0). The nonparametric Mann-Whitney U test for two independent samples
was used to analyze quantave variables (the number of personal and data sources and visualizaons). This decision
was made on the basis of the sample size and the nonsasfacon of normality (as determined by the Kolmogorov-Smir-
nov test). A chi-squared test (χ
2
) was applied for all other variables to idenfy signicant dierences between the Spani-
sh newspaper El país and the Austrian newspaper Der standard. Yates’ connuity correcon (χ
y
2
) was applied when there
was only one degree of freedom. If stascal signicance was detected (p≤0.05), we calculated the eect size (ES) and
analyzed the standardized residuals. For both, the condence level was set at 95%.
2.3. Interviews
We conducted focused interviews with members of the data journalism teams of El país and Der standard. This techni-
que is considered the most suitable approach to deal with innovaons in this area (Arias-Robles; López-López, 2020),
and it enabled us to explore the posion of each media outlet. The interviewees were located and contacted through
Twier and corporave email. Owing to the explorave nature of this study, we talked to only one journalist per news-
room. On the basis of relevance criteria and availability, we interviewed Daniele Grasso, Coordinator of the Data Journa-
lism Unit at El país, and Michael Matzenberger, Head of Data Journalism / Interacve, at Der standard. The interviews,
lasng between 60 and 75 minutes, were conducted online via Google Meet between October and December 2021. The
conversaons were recorded and manually transcribed. A quesonnaire comprising 16 quesons was used, organized
into three themac areas related to the research quesons: (a) the organizaonal structure of data teams and the com-
mon features of day-to-day data-driven stories; (b) quality data journalism, access to informaon, and protability; and
(c) the current status and future developments of data-driven reporng.
3. Results
3.1. Features of data-driven stories
The results of the content analysis reveal the dierences between and similaries of the data journalism pracces in
Spain and Austria. In total, 136 data-driven stories were published during the period examined: 99 in El país (72.8%) and
37 in Der standard (27.2%). On average, the names of two journalists were menoned per news story (ME=2; standard
deviaon [SD]=1.84).

that examined data about the coronavirus pandemic were especially common (Table 2). The results highlighted the sig-

stories about polics (36.4%), in Der standard, business (24.3%) and social issues (18.3%) were the most frequently
covered topics.

Following these insights into the content of the news stories analyzed, below we present the ndings from the inter-
views with the journalists from El país and Der standard.
3.2. Organizaon of the teams and creaon of data-driven stories
The El país data team is formed of three journalists with dierent proles, integrated into the “Visual Narraves” group,
which is made up of around ten people, including gures such as designers and developers. This team plays a cross-func-
onal role in the newsroom, and they usually work together in all steps. The Der standard data unit has a similar struc-
ture, with four members with well-dened proles. However, only the head of the team has a permanent full-me
contract, which makes it dicult to create pieces on a connuous basis. As at El país, it has a transversal role, but there is
a clear division of tasks, especially regarding technical funcons such as programming, analysis, or interacon. Although
the producon process of data-driven stories is not standardized, both the Spanish and Austrian newspapers include
four key steps:
(1) Choice and concepon of the project, which consists of focusing on the topic, searching for sources of informaon,
and previous research.
(2) Analysis of the dataset, which is the most extensive stage because the framework is established here; this includes
cleaning up the gures and asking the right quesons about the data.

(4) Publicaon, which involves selecng the suitable tool
and visualizaons to communicate the results.
The team spirit at the Spanish media outlet is very similar to at the Austrian one. Nevertheless, the main dierence is
the allocaon of tasks during the producon process. While in Der standard each member is responsible for a part of the
story and these are combined at the end, at El país all the decisions are jointly made. El país devotes at least ve days to
publishing a data-driven story. Daniele Grasso noted,
“We try not to tread on the daily journalism because data analysis requires me and that does not t in with the
speed of publicaon of a newspaper. From the beginning, we made it clear to our bosses: if they want good work,
it cannot be done in one day. That does not mean that we are not able to produce arcles in a morning as we have
done with Covid or elecon results.”
The Der standard data team ensure that they can oer immediacy because they mostly depend on other secons. To
a lesser extent –especially when they propose their own topics– they publish stories with a longer producon process.
For El país, the main obstacles to data journalism pracce are the formats in which the public instuons publish their
data –hindering their reuse– and the lack of availability of certain gures. In Austria, there are even greater problems. In
addion to immediacy, there are also limitaons related to access to informaon. Marzenberger explained,
“We denitely have a real problem in Austria. The Covid pandemic showed that authories hide data and ignore
our enquiries. Even some available and anonymized data is restrained under the cloak of privacy. On top of that
we have to add endless bureaucracy to get access to public databases, which makes our work more dicult and
makes it not worthwhile to spend me requesng data.”
3.3. Quality data journalism, access to informaon, and protability
El país maintains that quality data journalism work should be interesng, useful, and transparent. Grasso stated that
“there are no elements that determine the quality of a project; the main objecve pursued by its publicaon is
what makes it a good piece.”
However, he insisted on the importance of incorporang how data is collected and how these conclusions have been
reached to provide solvency to the arcle. In the same vein, Der standard also states that a good data story must comply
with journalisc principles, and its quality will be determined by the news value of the informaon.
Both the Spanish and the Austrian newspapers agree that data journalism is more well-recognized and developed in
countries with eecve access-to-informaon laws. Although the Spanish legislaon has its shortcomings, the lack of
guidelines in terms of access to informaon in Austria makes data journalism pracces more dicult.
“[In Spain] The transparency council should have more power. It should not be an agency that only urges on
paper, but it should enforce the law. That could mean a leap in quality and to duck out once quesoned by the
cizen would be impossible for the instuons,” Grasso said.
Michael Matzenberger explained that
“some opposion pares and civil acvists have been ghng for years to bring a transparency law on track, yet
we do not know if and to what extent it will become true.”
The El país journalist asserted that their readers are in-
terested in data journalism based on reading me and
the online reach of their publicaons. This has been de-
monstrated with the current subscripon model of this
media outlet, too. He also stated that this specializaon
“is protable” because it helps to add dierenaon from the compeon and allows them to build dierent and varied
stories. The same is true for Der standard, which claimed that data-driven stories published during the pandemic are the
most visited pages in their history and that these works have demonstrated the need for reliable data to make decisions.
However, the team members do not feel suciently valued in their own newsroom.
“Our colleagues come to us to improve their stories, but they do not see us as indispensable. It would not really
maer if our team broke away,” Matzenberger stated.
3.4. Insights into the state and the future of data journalism
Daniele Grasso conrmed the exponenal rise of data journalism in Spain in recent years.
“It is a type of journalism that has proved to be very useful. So useful that people think of it as good journalism
and not as something specic.” (Grasso)

Despite this rise, Grasso stated that Spanish data journa-

In Austria, data journalism is sll underrepresented. Although the Der standard data team is formed of only four people,
Michael Matzenberger argued that they are one of the largest data teams in the country. The Austrian journalist pointed
to execuve and management posions and the poor recognion of the potenal of data journalism as the main reasons
for this situaon in Austria. This results in a lack of funding and resources to address data-driven stories.
In this sense, the journalists at both El país and Der standard predicted that data journalism will develop constantly.
Grasso forecasted that the “data journalism” label will be diluted and treated as an intrinsic part of journalism.
“Using graphs and maps in works based on hundreds of thousands of data will become so common that there will
be no need to include the data journalism label,” said Grasso.
Meanwhile, according to Matzenberger, data journalism will connue to evolve. Unfortunately, unless the situaon is
reversed, Austria will remain at lower levels in this aspect, not in terms of educaon –journalism training for data work
at university or schools– but on the professional side.
4. Discussion and conclusions
The aim of this study was to explore data-driven journalism in terms of the content of news stories and journalisc prac-
ces and rounes. The results of this study present strong connecons with previous work, but this study allows us to
delve deeper into the state of data journalism in underexplored countries such as Spain and Austria. The ndings from
the content analysis and interviews reect the disparity of contexts in which data journalism is carried out, the common
features, the organizaonal structure, the limitaons, and the prospects for the specializaon in these countries.
The analysis reveals a general prole of the works published in Der standard and El país and highlights the similaries
of and dierences between these two newspapers (RQ1). Health, science, and environment is the prevailing topic. This
conrms that this topic is a determining issue corresponding to the me of publicaon. They coincide in giving more
space to arcles about the coronavirus pandemic, but dier in oering space to polics –which is more represented in
El país– and to economy or social issues –which is more represented in Der standard. These dierences reect the trans-
versality of the tool, which is adaptable to any themac area (RQ1a).
Although adding personal sources is uncommon in day-to-day data journalism, it is more frequent at the Austrian outlet.
In regard to incorporang, the vast majority opt for experts in a eld to complete the informaon. As regards narrave
style, Der standard chose an explanatory structure (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018), while El país
preferred to combine explanatory and exploratory styles with some freedom for interacon (Córdoba-Cabús; García-Bo-
rrego; López-Marn, 2020).
The projects are almost enrely data-driven stories whose main goal is to inform and to explain what happens. The scant
presence of deep invesgaons during the period under review reveals the pressure for immediacy and a lack of me
to deal with other issues. The most common way of communicang numerical informaon is to combine narrave and
visualizaon (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Córdoba-Cabús, 2020;
Rubio-Jordán, 2021). Data journalism arcles can be displayed through a variety of forms. However, it has been demons-
trated that visualizaon plays a key role in this discipline.
The analyzed data-driven stories incorporated two data sources on average, and they mainly relied on government sour-
ces, which is in line with previous research from other countries (Parasie; Darigal, 2012; Knight, 2015; De-Maeyer et al.,
2015; Cushion; Lewis; Callaghan, 2017; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Stalph, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018;
Appelgren, 2018; Hyder; Nahid, 2019). The problems regarding access to public informaon in Austria are reected in
the use of the news outlets’ own sources. Unlike El país, Der standard relied more on its own surveys and experiments to
produce its own data for its news stories. This strategy allowed it to overcome the opacity of the Austrian administraon.
Although transparency is considered to be a fundamental element in data journalism stories, this characterisc is scarce
in day-to-day arcles according to previous studies (Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Stalph, 2018;
Zhang; Feng, 2019; Zamith, 2019; Córdoba-Cabús; García-Borrego, 2021). While the vast majority of arcles cite sour-
ces directly, linking to datasets and adding a methodological secon remains rare. Zamith (2019, p. 15) stated that
“journalists may not priorize leading readers to
source material when aempng to meet deadli-
nes during their day-to-day work or acvely resist
ceding too much autonomy through over-sha-
ring.”
The scant presence of deep investiga-
tions during the period under review re-
veals the pressure for immediacy and a
lack of time to deal with other issues

In this sense, El país diers from Der standard. The Spa-
nish outlet meets the idealized form of transparency on
more occasions (RQ1b). This may be due to the lack of
resources, me, and knowledge to provide such open-
ness (Córdoba-Cabús; García-Borrego, 2021) or, as men-
oned by Porlezza and Splendore (2019, p. 1246), “be-
cause of the fear of free-riding by the competors,” which could involve copying or replicang their work.
The strategy in terms of visualizaons and interacvity also diers (RQ1c). While El país added interacve graphs, Der
standard opted for stac graphs. Despite these divergences, the ndings reinforce the idea of reduced interacvity (Loo-
sen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Stalph, 2018; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Córdo-
ba-Cabús; García-Borrego, 2020). This decrease in interacvity is closely aligned with the addion of simpler and more
basic interacve features in visualizaons, such as exploraon. As pointed out by Appelgren (2018),
“The illusion of interacvity thus replaces real interacvity.”
The projects increasingly employ perceived interacvity, which gave the audience a sense of control, while the author
actually retained full control.
The interviews conrmed that the context strongly condions how data journalism is carried out (Appelgren; Nygren,
2014; Appelgren; Salaverría, 2018; Sandoval-Marn; La-Rosa, 2018; Porlezza; Splendore, 2019). On the one hand, the
incipient status of data journalism in Austria is mainly due to the lack of guidelines in terms of access to informaon
(RQ2). Moreover, there is an absence of awareness of their value, which implies a lack of recognion even within their
own newspaper. As Tong (2022, p. 2795) stated,
“Data journalists’ experse, together with the increasing internal recognion and their compelling data stories,
helps them establish cultural authority.”
On the other hand, at El país, the working schedule is respected and data journalism is used as a feature to dierenate
it from the compeon. The arcles produced during the analyzed period reveal the dierence in this regard (99 news
stories published in El país and 37 in Der standard). The situaon of Austrian data journalism is more similar to that in
Arab countries (Lewis; Nashmi, 2019; Mutsvairo; Bebawi; Borges-Rey, 2020) than to that in European countries. Aus-
trian data journalists face all the obstacles menoned in the scienc literature, both internal –within the newsrooms–
and external –related to the context (Appelgren; Lindén; Van-Dalen, 2019; Kashyap; Bhaskaran; Mishra, 2020).
The data teams –based on the number of workers– and the producon process of a data journalism story are similar in El
país and Der standard. Although the inverted pyramid proposed by Bradshaw (2011) is called into queson (Albert-Trini-
dad, 2020), these ndings show that data-driven arcles are produced according to these phases. The dierences lie in
the organizaonal structure of the data teams and in the contractual relaonships with each company. Data journalists
in El país work together in all steps and have permanent full-me contracts. However, a division of tasks prevails in Der
standard, and the members of the data journalism team are hired part-me.
The percepons about the future of data journalism are in line with Stalph and Borges-Rey (2018) and Ëkström and
Westlund (2019): Data will become an inherent part of journalism, and it will be essenal to all journalisc publicaons
(RQ3). Journalists at both El país and Der standard believe that data journalism will grow and evolve. Nevertheless, obs-
tacles in Austria are expected to connue to limit the pracce of data journalism.
This study is not free of limitaons. First, our sample for the content analysis was limited. We were only able to analyze
one newspaper per country. Hence, future studies should extend such analysis to other newspapers that pracce data
journalism in dierent countries. In addion, it would be interesng to analyze changes over me and to deepen our
understanding of the impact of data journalism on society.
Notwithstanding these limitaons, this study was able to deliver important inial insights into day-to-day data jour-
nalism content and work rounes in Spain and Austria. The pracce of data journalism in Austria and Spain mainly
diers because of the context in which it is carried out.
This research conrms the relevance that this speciali-
zaon is currently acquiring in countries such as Spain
and demonstrates the challenges that journalists face in
countries without access to informaon and transparen-
cy laws to build good stories with data.
